WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.260 --> 00:00:01.350
MOONLIT BESHIMOV:
My name is Moonlit.

00:00:01.350 --> 00:00:01.818
AUDIENCE: Woo!

00:00:01.818 --> 00:00:02.317
Woo!

00:00:02.317 --> 00:00:04.239
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:04.239 --> 00:00:06.780
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: I'm a partner
development manager at Google

00:00:06.780 --> 00:00:09.750
Play, specializing in games.

00:00:09.750 --> 00:00:13.290
I am keenly aware that I am
one of the last two things

00:00:13.290 --> 00:00:16.420
standing between
you and Happy Hour.

00:00:16.420 --> 00:00:19.050
So let's look at something fun.

00:00:19.050 --> 00:00:21.270
What are some of the
recent trends in innovation

00:00:21.270 --> 00:00:25.290
in mobile gaming,
specifically, genre mashing

00:00:25.290 --> 00:00:27.730
and subscriptions?

00:00:27.730 --> 00:00:29.980
You probably noticed
my cheerleading squad

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:31.630
sitting here.

00:00:31.630 --> 00:00:34.210
We're lucky to have
Lauren, Chris, and Charles

00:00:34.210 --> 00:00:37.840
from three of our top
partners join me on stage.

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:39.890
You'll hear from
each one of them

00:00:39.890 --> 00:00:42.670
their stories of innovation.

00:00:42.670 --> 00:00:45.500
But first, let me set the stage.

00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:48.470
Today, we'll cover
these three things.

00:00:48.470 --> 00:00:51.850
First, I'll give you an
overview of the global trends

00:00:51.850 --> 00:00:55.660
around genre mashing
within mobile gaming.

00:00:55.660 --> 00:00:58.720
Second, we'll show you
that this trend is not

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:01.330
limited to just mashing games.

00:01:01.330 --> 00:01:02.830
Our three guests
here will show you

00:01:02.830 --> 00:01:06.310
how they took genre
mashing beyond gaming

00:01:06.310 --> 00:01:10.070
by bringing in three very
different industries.

00:01:10.070 --> 00:01:11.900
And last, we'll
touch on a little bit

00:01:11.900 --> 00:01:15.660
of monetization innovation
recently, namely subscriptions

00:01:15.660 --> 00:01:18.180
in mobile gaming.

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:22.300
All right, let's talk about
genre mashing within gaming.

00:01:22.300 --> 00:01:25.090
The idea of combining
multiple core game

00:01:25.090 --> 00:01:27.850
loops into the same
game on mobile,

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:30.580
it's not a recent phenomenon.

00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:34.150
In 2012, GungHo swept
the world with launch

00:01:34.150 --> 00:01:39.550
of "Puzzle" and "Dragons,"
the godfather of puzzle RPG.

00:01:39.550 --> 00:01:43.060
Then in 2014, "Summoners
War" by Com2uS

00:01:43.060 --> 00:01:49.200
kickstarted the era of CC
RPG or card collecting RPG.

00:01:49.200 --> 00:01:54.790
It also kickstarted the era of
long acronyms in mobile gaming.

00:01:54.790 --> 00:01:57.130
So consider this a
forewarning for the amount

00:01:57.130 --> 00:02:00.760
of acronyms I'm going to use
in the next five minutes.

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:03.660
Today, genre mashing
happens all over the world

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:07.330
in mobile gaming, from
the most casual, to core,

00:02:07.330 --> 00:02:09.400
to beyond gaming.

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:11.950
Next, I'll share with you
some testimonies and case

00:02:11.950 --> 00:02:17.090
studies from the top mobile game
developers around the world.

00:02:17.090 --> 00:02:20.710
On the more casual end,
we have Rodeo Stampede--

00:02:20.710 --> 00:02:24.140
an endless runner game
with builder meta.

00:02:24.140 --> 00:02:26.510
Featherweight, the
Australian developer,

00:02:26.510 --> 00:02:29.700
with Yodo1, the
Chinese publisher,

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:33.455
used genre mashing as
a way to differentiate,

00:02:33.455 --> 00:02:34.830
turning something
that would have

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:40.950
been a subtle twist into
something much more unique.

00:02:40.950 --> 00:02:44.910
The game-- this innovation--
has won them multiple awards

00:02:44.910 --> 00:02:48.900
and helped the game
go viral globally.

00:02:48.900 --> 00:02:53.610
"Gardenscapes" is probably one
of the most iconic successes

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:56.160
of genre mashing
in mobile gaming.

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:59.410
Playrix, the Russian
game developer,

00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:02.610
see genre mashing as a way
to stand out from the crowded

00:03:02.610 --> 00:03:04.740
and established market.

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:07.650
Something we also observed
earlier in Emily's talk

00:03:07.650 --> 00:03:09.690
on de-risking your launch.

00:03:09.690 --> 00:03:14.370
Playrix brilliantly
interweaves two core games

00:03:14.370 --> 00:03:16.650
their core audience loves--

00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:19.230
match-3 and builder.

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:23.910
The result is incredible player
love, loyalty, and growth.

00:03:23.910 --> 00:03:29.250
The game is top grossing
globally, including Asia.

00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:31.920
Now, moving on to
value more core--

00:03:31.920 --> 00:03:35.760
"Castle Crush" by TFG, a
Brazilian game developer,

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:39.030
combined the elements
of combat strategy game

00:03:39.030 --> 00:03:42.340
with that of traditional
trading card game--

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:45.180
kind of like "Magic,
the Gathering."

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:47.460
The game only launching
June this year,

00:03:47.460 --> 00:03:49.920
and it already has more
than 5 million installs,

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:51.450
with a 4.5-star rating.

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:58.280
"Lords Mobile" is a
real-time MMO strategy

00:03:58.280 --> 00:04:02.760
game with the colorful
elements of an RPG.

00:04:02.760 --> 00:04:05.570
IGG, the game developer,
sees genre mashing

00:04:05.570 --> 00:04:08.570
as a way to meet the
demand of their users

00:04:08.570 --> 00:04:11.630
for more sophisticated games.

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:14.450
They also see it as a way
to bring a new experience

00:04:14.450 --> 00:04:17.720
for users who might otherwise
not try a different genre.

00:04:20.570 --> 00:04:24.230
"Magic Rush" by Moonton
Elex, Chinese developer

00:04:24.230 --> 00:04:29.100
and publisher, is a fresh
combination of three genres.

00:04:29.100 --> 00:04:32.840
Moonton created "Magic Rush"
as a global entry point.

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:36.890
By studying user pattern
and demand around the globe,

00:04:36.890 --> 00:04:39.980
they learned that RPG
has been popular in Asia,

00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:42.860
whereas combat strategy
games perform really

00:04:42.860 --> 00:04:45.580
well in Europe and America.

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:48.500
So "Magic Rush"
was born as the way

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:51.470
to improve upon
the elements of RPG

00:04:51.470 --> 00:04:54.650
with the swipe action
of tower defense games

00:04:54.650 --> 00:04:59.430
and the social appeal of SLG.

00:04:59.430 --> 00:05:01.960
But enough talking
about mashing games.

00:05:01.960 --> 00:05:04.660
I'm going to turn it over
to my guest speakers, who

00:05:04.660 --> 00:05:07.780
will share with you
how they reinvented fun

00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:12.160
by mashing gaming with three
very different industries.

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:14.050
First, we'll hear
from Pocket Gems

00:05:14.050 --> 00:05:16.690
about "Episode
Interactive," a game that's

00:05:16.690 --> 00:05:20.290
turning into a new
medium for storytelling.

00:05:20.290 --> 00:05:22.330
And then we'll have
Crowdstar to tell you

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:25.330
about their recent hit,
"Design Home," which

00:05:25.330 --> 00:05:30.310
presents mobile game as a canvas
for design and creativity.

00:05:30.310 --> 00:05:32.260
And last, we'll
hear from Workshop

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:34.390
about how they're
turning mobile gaming

00:05:34.390 --> 00:05:38.320
into a new channel for music.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:40.730
These are my star presenters.

00:05:40.730 --> 00:05:44.360
First, let's welcome Lauren
Luke from Pocket Gems.

