00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:39.240
Well, "Design Home" is a
3D interior design game.

00:10:39.240 --> 00:10:45.060
It's essentially an endless
dollhouse but for grown-ups.

00:10:45.060 --> 00:10:46.860
And before I talk
about "Design Home,"

00:10:46.860 --> 00:10:49.110
I want to talk a little
bit about the philosophy

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:51.260
of the studio I work
for called Crowdstar.

00:10:51.260 --> 00:10:54.120
Because Crowdstar has
actually been mashing up

00:10:54.120 --> 00:10:57.660
reality-based design
games for five years,

00:10:57.660 --> 00:11:00.840
first with the hit "Covet
Fashion" in the fashion

00:11:00.840 --> 00:11:04.650
space, which after five years
is still going very strong,

00:11:04.650 --> 00:11:06.150
and now with "Design
Home," which we

00:11:06.150 --> 00:11:08.160
launched about 11 months ago.

00:11:08.160 --> 00:11:13.140
And to be honest with you,
Crowdstar was born in a moment

00:11:13.140 --> 00:11:15.930
of desperation-- or at
least the current iteration

00:11:15.930 --> 00:11:17.190
of Crowdstar--

00:11:17.190 --> 00:11:19.500
when they realized
that they had better

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:21.840
do something different
and something bold,

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:25.050
or they were going to
die a certain death.

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:27.480
And what they did, and I
wasn't there at the time,

00:11:27.480 --> 00:11:30.251
is really look for
the white space.

00:11:30.251 --> 00:11:32.250
And what they found was
there was a huge segment

00:11:32.250 --> 00:11:35.310
of people that were totally
under-served by the gaming

00:11:35.310 --> 00:11:37.950
market in something that
not only would enthrall them

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:40.110
but also would help
them in their real life.

00:11:40.110 --> 00:11:41.430
And that segment was women--

00:11:41.430 --> 00:11:43.950
not girls but women.

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:47.790
And they have a
different mindset really.

00:11:47.790 --> 00:11:51.840
These are women who are coming
into their own financially.

00:11:51.840 --> 00:11:54.750
They are highly engaged,
highly creative.

00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:58.140
They often are
focused on somebody--

00:11:58.140 --> 00:12:03.300
on people that aren't always
themselves, namely families.

00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:07.580
And this is a creative
canvas for them

00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:11.810
to not only express
their creativity

00:12:11.810 --> 00:12:14.810
but apply it to real life.

00:12:14.810 --> 00:12:16.590
And it's a positive sum game.

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:20.790
We always make sure it
is a positive sum game.

00:12:20.790 --> 00:12:23.440
OK, so what do we do?

00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:26.390
Well, we partner
with real brands.

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:31.190
We model real products, and
we put them into 3D settings.

00:12:31.190 --> 00:12:33.200
We're essentially
changing the conversation

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:36.470
between makers and consumers,
so that makers aren't just

00:12:36.470 --> 00:12:39.620
talking at consumers.

00:12:39.620 --> 00:12:41.090
We're giving the
consumers a chance

00:12:41.090 --> 00:12:44.870
to play with products
in a fun atmosphere,

00:12:44.870 --> 00:12:47.450
and it always comes with links,
so that you can buy things

00:12:47.450 --> 00:12:49.110
in the real world.

00:12:49.110 --> 00:12:51.770
So for example, we
have dozens and dozens

00:12:51.770 --> 00:12:53.300
of real furniture partners.

00:12:53.300 --> 00:12:58.190
Some bigs, and we also go
and find niche boutiques.

00:12:58.190 --> 00:13:01.310
And to date, we've
modeled 6,700 products,

00:13:01.310 --> 00:13:02.960
and that grows every single day.

00:13:07.250 --> 00:13:10.430
It's a very simple game loop.

00:13:10.430 --> 00:13:13.770
It's shop, design, win.

00:13:13.770 --> 00:13:16.480
It opens up a world
of content experiences

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:21.340
that you just can't do, you
can't do in your own home.

00:13:21.340 --> 00:13:23.980
You get to mix and match and
visualize completed designs

00:13:23.980 --> 00:13:27.160
in a way that mood boards
could never duplicate.

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:29.740
We launch five challenges--
hand-crafted challenges--

00:13:29.740 --> 00:13:31.330
a day.

00:13:31.330 --> 00:13:33.320
They stay open for three days.

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:35.710
And once you're done with
your design, you submit it,

00:13:35.710 --> 00:13:38.967
and it gets scored,
frankly, by the audience.

00:13:38.967 --> 00:13:41.050
So it goes in and other
people vote on what's good

00:13:41.050 --> 00:13:42.580
and what's not.

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:44.350
You get back your score.

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:45.710
You get virtual prizes.

00:13:45.710 --> 00:13:47.810
So everybody is happy.

00:13:47.810 --> 00:13:50.350
And then you also see
what the winning designs

00:13:50.350 --> 00:13:52.180
were, the highest
score so that you

00:13:52.180 --> 00:13:55.540
can see what you might have done
better or what goes with what.

00:13:55.540 --> 00:13:58.850
So there's always a
learning experience.

00:13:58.850 --> 00:14:01.840
And it's a mixture of
highly relatable settings,

00:14:01.840 --> 00:14:07.350
whether it's a suburban
house in Erie, Pennsylvania,

00:14:07.350 --> 00:14:12.340
to an apartment in New York,
to aspirational settings

00:14:12.340 --> 00:14:14.316
like a tropical island.

00:14:14.316 --> 00:14:15.940
And then we have some
fantasy settings.

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:18.250
So you could be
designing a moonbase.

00:14:18.250 --> 00:14:20.510
Or like at Christmastime,
one of my personal favorites

00:14:20.510 --> 00:14:23.530
was you did the interior
of a gingerbread house.

00:14:23.530 --> 00:14:25.370
It's simple, and it's fun.

00:14:29.870 --> 00:14:34.310
But it turns out that modeling
reality is really hard,

00:14:34.310 --> 00:14:37.650
and I'm blessed to work with
some incredible producers,

00:14:37.650 --> 00:14:40.880
engineers, and artists
because the standards that you

00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:44.270
have to reach to model
reality are really high.

00:14:44.270 --> 00:14:46.460
These are not
stylized characters

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:48.080
running around a screen.

00:14:48.080 --> 00:14:50.210
You have to figure
out, not only model

00:14:50.210 --> 00:14:52.660
the furniture and
the decor perfectly,

00:14:52.660 --> 00:14:53.660
but the room has to fit.

00:14:53.660 --> 00:14:54.680
You have to figure
out the lighting.

00:14:54.680 --> 00:14:56.888
You have to figure out the
shadows and how everything

00:14:56.888 --> 00:14:59.470
is going to go together when
you have thousands of products

00:14:59.470 --> 00:15:02.300
that the user might use.

00:15:02.300 --> 00:15:08.930
So, and then you have to also
run a handcrafted live ops,

00:15:08.930 --> 00:15:10.640
which is just really intense.

00:15:10.640 --> 00:15:14.780
And again, I'm super
blessed with the people

00:15:14.780 --> 00:15:15.770
that I work with.

00:15:15.770 --> 00:15:19.430
And while we're happy
with the aesthetics now,

00:15:19.430 --> 00:15:23.050
you can imagine where
this space is going.

00:15:23.050 --> 00:15:26.770
I mean our objective is to be
able to fall into the room--

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:28.750
to taste the air in the room.

00:15:28.750 --> 00:15:35.680
And with AR, VR, and lots
of other possible Rs coming,

00:15:35.680 --> 00:15:38.695
it's a pretty exciting
and dynamic space.

00:15:38.695 --> 00:15:40.510
I'm enthralled on
really where it can go.

00:15:43.290 --> 00:15:47.100
So, so far, we were
launched in November 15th.

00:15:47.100 --> 00:15:50.400
So we're coming up on
our one year birthday.

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:52.410
Through June, which is
what I can talk about now

00:15:52.410 --> 00:15:54.650
that we're a publicly
traded company because we

00:15:54.650 --> 00:15:59.580
were acquired by Glu, we've
had 25 million downloads.

00:15:59.580 --> 00:16:02.090
We've exceeded a
million users every day.

00:16:02.090 --> 00:16:04.905
We've done a little more
than $40 million in bookings.

00:16:04.905 --> 00:16:06.780
But I think really the
most interesting thing

00:16:06.780 --> 00:16:11.580
is that our users are
generating more than 2 million

00:16:11.580 --> 00:16:14.070
handcrafted rooms a day.

00:16:14.070 --> 00:16:16.740
We've built a house of
over 500 million rooms.

00:16:16.740 --> 00:16:19.270
I think we're just
getting started.

00:16:19.270 --> 00:16:22.130
And thanks for your time.

00:16:22.130 --> 00:16:23.630
I'll buy you a drink
at the bar if--

00:16:23.630 --> 00:16:24.179
later.

00:16:24.179 --> 00:16:26.220
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Now,
you've heard from Workshop

00:16:26.220 --> 00:16:28.940
how they're thinking about
their subscription design.

00:16:28.940 --> 00:16:32.670
I want to also share with
you some best practices.

00:16:32.670 --> 00:16:34.800
There are two main ways
of using subscription

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:36.510
in your mobile games.

00:16:36.510 --> 00:16:39.760
One, we have subscription VIP.

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:42.550
Two, we have subscription IAP.

00:16:42.550 --> 00:16:45.300
I promise I'm not going to rap.

00:16:45.300 --> 00:16:49.930
Subscription VIP-- it's all
about the high-value users.

00:16:49.930 --> 00:16:52.650
These users are
motivated by prestige,

00:16:52.650 --> 00:16:55.230
vanity, loyalty rewards.

00:16:55.230 --> 00:16:58.200
So your goal as a developer
is to really increase

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:01.660
long-term retention,
total revenue,

00:17:01.660 --> 00:17:05.069
the loyalty from the payers
and also other players.

00:17:05.069 --> 00:17:08.130
Some examples of
subscription VIP design

00:17:08.130 --> 00:17:11.550
include exclusive
and/or early access

00:17:11.550 --> 00:17:15.569
to special content,
specific and special promos

00:17:15.569 --> 00:17:20.760
for these subscribers, and
also higher daily caps.

00:17:20.760 --> 00:17:23.099
For subscription
IAP, you should be

00:17:23.099 --> 00:17:25.440
thinking about targeting
everybody else--

00:17:25.440 --> 00:17:28.930
but especially, the non-buyers.

00:17:28.930 --> 00:17:32.820
These people are motivated by
getting a good financial deal.

00:17:32.820 --> 00:17:35.940
So your goal as a developer
is to really increase

00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:40.410
buyer retention and cultivate
the habit of logging in daily

00:17:40.410 --> 00:17:42.540
to increase your LTV.

00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:45.720
So some example of
subscription IAP design

00:17:45.720 --> 00:17:48.390
include having a SKU
of gems that pay out

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:50.280
over several periods of time--

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:52.200
several days, for example.

00:17:52.200 --> 00:17:54.450
This will help
players come back in

00:17:54.450 --> 00:17:57.780
and log in daily to
claim the rewards.

00:17:57.780 --> 00:18:00.840
As with all subscription
and monetization design,

00:18:00.840 --> 00:18:03.450
really keep track
of the downsides.

00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:05.670
Be careful of
cannibalization, and keep

00:18:05.670 --> 00:18:11.070
a close pulse of your pillar of
sentiment among your community.

00:18:11.070 --> 00:18:13.766
Now, talking about trends
and innovations fun,

00:18:13.766 --> 00:18:15.390
I also want to leave
you with something

00:18:15.390 --> 00:18:18.330
to take with you as you
head into Happy Hour

00:18:18.330 --> 00:18:21.910
after the next session.

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:23.470
So let's summarize.

00:18:23.470 --> 00:18:27.540
Genre mashing should be used
for, one, differentiation,

00:18:27.540 --> 00:18:31.440
or two, as a new way
to consume content.

00:18:31.440 --> 00:18:36.960
Subscriptions should be used
for, one, VIP to identify VIP,

00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:41.130
to encourage engagement,
to increase loyalty.

00:18:41.130 --> 00:18:43.350
And subscription
IAP should be used

00:18:43.350 --> 00:18:47.040
to offer a good deal for
people who might otherwise not

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:50.490
spend in your games.

00:18:50.490 --> 00:18:52.920
Now, thank you,
and thanks, Lauren.

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:55.650
Thanks, Charles and Chris for
an amazing talk and sharing

00:18:55.650 --> 00:18:57.770
with us your experience.

00:18:57.770 --> 00:18:59.270
Let's give them a
round of applause.

